<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONFICTION IN BRIEF: INTERFERENCE: HOW ORGANIZED CRIME INFLUENCES PROFESSIONAL
FOOTBALL BY DAN E. MOLDEA (WILLIAM MORROW: $19.95; 436 PP.)
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Harris, Column edited by Sonja Bolle.
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Most Americans," Dan E. Moldea says, "view sports as a vehicle of inspiration
and entertainment" -- and as something to bet on. The estimated 25 million
people who wager tens of billions of dollars on National Football League games
each year eagerly accept the NFL's assurances that these games are honest. They
don't know, or don't care, that the 10% "vigorish" that bookmakers charge on
losing NFL bets provides the underworld with more illegal gambling income than
all other sports combined. They prefer to believe that the league has
rigorously investigated gambling and drug scandals, that team owners are
sportsmen and that players always give their best. These are myths, Moldea
says, but "powerful forces in America have built empires around these myths."
</P>
<P>
The truth is quite different, according to Moldea, a veteran crime reporter
whose last book was "Dark Victory: Ronald Reagan, MCA and the Mob." The NFL
claims that gamblers have made only two attempts, both unsuccessful, to fix
games in the league's 60-year history. Instead, Moldea says, as many as 70
games may have been fixed outright or manipulated to affect the point spread
set by mob-connected oddsmakers. Even when games are honest, gamblers use their
close ties to the NFL to gain inside information. Widespread drug use by
players gives the mob even more leverage. What Moldea calls "the sweetheart
relationship between the federal government and the NFL" has reduced many a
promising investigation into the league's dirty secrets to the equivalent of
three downs and a punt.
</P>
<P>
"Interference," in contrast, is like a hard-nosed fullback, gracelessly written
but packed with names, dates and places, hitting the holes until the defense --
one's incredulity -- gives way. This is not the first time such accusations
have been hurled; longtime NFL Commissioner Pete Rozelle dismissed a 1983 PBS
TV expose of the league as "a rehash of press clippings, gossip and rumor."
Moldea's targets could say the same, but the weight of evidence is
overwhelming. Moldea, shows, for example, how former Los Angeles Rams owner
Carroll Rosenbloom partnered mob figures in business throughout his career. He
was also a heavy gambler who, when he owned the Baltimore Colts, bet $1 million
on them to win the 1958 NFL championship game with the New York Giants -- a sum
that puts the recent Pete Rose baseball scandal in perspective. And Rosenbloom,
Moldea makes clear, was -- and would be today -- just one of the boys. Michael
Harris
</P>
</TEXT>
